PMID: 26460688 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


38. Natl Vital Stat Rep. 2015 Sep 22;64(11):1-63.

United States Life Tables, 2011.

Arias E.

OBJECTIVES: This report presents complete period life tables for the United 
States by race, Hispanic origin, and sex, based on age specific death rates in 
2011.
METHODS: Data used to prepare the 2011 life tables are 2011 final mortality 
statistics; July 1, 2011, population estimates based on the 2010 decennial 
census; and 2011 Medicare data for persons aged 66-99. The methodology used to 
estimate the 2011 life tables was first implemented with data year 2008. The 
methodology used to estimated the life tables for the Hispanic population 
remains unchanged from that developed for the publication of life tables by 
Hispanic origin for data year 2006.
RESULTS: In 2011, the overall expectation of life at birth was 78.7 
years--unchanged from 2010. Between 2010 and 2011, life expectancy at birth 
increased for both males (from 76.2 to 76.3) and females (81.0-81.1), and for 
the white population (78.9 to 79.0), the black population (75.1 to 75.3), the 
Hispanic population *81.4 to 81.6), and the non-Hispanic black population (74.7 
to 74.9).

All material appearing in this report is in the public domain and may be 
reproduced or copied without permission; citation as to source, however, is 
appreciated.

